eu.cqse.check.framework.shallowparser.framework

Class ShallowEntity

  • java.lang.Object
    • eu.cqse.check.framework.shallowparser.framework.ShallowEntity
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DocumentRootShallowEntity

    public class ShallowEntity
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    An entity resulting from shallow parsing. For classes outside of this package, this class is immutable. An exception is made for addChild which can be overridden by subclasses. Entities represent classes, methods, statements, etc. Parser errors are usually marked by the inclusion of incomplete entities. For these entities, the end values (index, offset, etc.) may be wrong or even invalid.

      • isContinued

        public boolean isContinued()
        Returns whether this node is continued, which means that the next sibling node logically is associated to this one. This feature is used, e.g., to connect the if-block and the corresponding else-block, which are parsed into separate nodes, but the first (if) node will be marked as continued. Note that even if this is true, a next sibling might not exist (typically the result of parsing errors).

      • includedTokens

        public UnmodifiableList<IToken> includedTokens()

      • isEmpty

        public boolean isEmpty()
        Returns whether this is an empty entity, i.e. does not contain any tokens. An entity is empty only in very special cases, such as parsing files with invalid syntax.

      • ownTokens

        public java.util.List<UnmodifiableList<IToken>> ownTokens()
        Returns a view of the tokens (without comments) from the beginning of the entity up to the last token of the entity. It does not include the tokens of its children but it includes the tokens that may be arise between its children entities.

        Example: 

         double[] doubles = ints.stream().mapToDouble( //
                i -> i * 5.0 //
 ).filter(Double::isNaN).filter( //
                d -> d > 0 //
 ).toArray();
        Here, the entity's own tokens are spread across the following three subsequences:
        1. double[] doubles = ints.stream().mapToDouble(
        2. ).filter(Double::isNaN).filter(
        3. ).toArray();
        The returned list may thus contain more than just ownStartTokens() and ownEndTokens(), as lambda expressions may introduce an arbitrary number of children.

      • ownStartTokens

        public UnmodifiableList<IToken> ownStartTokens()
        Returns a view of the tokens (without comments) from the beginning of the entity up to the first token included in the first child. For example for an if-block statement, this would include everything from the "if" to the first brace (inclusive). The first token of the first child statement would not be included. For an entity without children this will return includedTokens().

      • ownEndTokens

        public UnmodifiableList<IToken> ownEndTokens()
        For entities with children (hasChildren()), this returns a view of the tokens (without comments) from the last token included in the last child up to the end of the entity. For example for a do-while statement, this would include everything from (inclusive) the RBRACE closing the body to the end of the "while". The last token of the last child statement would not be included. Returns an empty list if called for an entity without children.
